# Build context allowlist-by-denial. Anything Docker sees here ends
# up baked into image layers OR bloats the build context upload. The
# rule of thumb is: nothing under 100 MB should land in the build
# context unless the multi-stage Dockerfile is going to copy it.

# Vendored deps + framework caches — pulled fresh in the build stage.
node_modules
.next
web/out
web/.next
.pnpm-store

# Source-control + IDE noise.
.git
.gitignore
.claude
.vscode
.idea
.DS_Store

# Docs — README is the one exception so /healthz hint endpoints can
# reference it.
*.md
!README.md

# Local-only secrets / env. Building must NEVER capture these.
.env*

# Local docker-compose files. The production Dockerfile is the only
# thing the build stage cares about; compose YAMLs would just inflate
# the build context.
docker/docker-compose*.yml
docker/crewshipd

# Multi-instance dev tree (crewship_1/, crewship_2/, ...).
crewship_*

# Audit artefacts (raw tool outputs, payload corpora, iteration reports)
# — multi-megabyte tree that has nothing to do with the runtime image.
# Audit M16 specifically flagged this leak.
audit
tmp

# Compiled local binaries + SQLite snapshots from `go run` /
# `dev.sh seed`. The Docker build produces its own binary in a
# distroless / alpine stage; the host's binary would only shadow it.
crewship
crewship.db
crewship.db-*

# Test + profile + coverage artefacts. Generated locally, never
# needed inside the image. `*.out` is intentionally not used as a
# global denial because it's too broad (some tooling produces .out
# files that are checked in); coverage.out is the only one we ship
# from go test, and `coverage.*` covers the variants.
*.test
*.prof
coverage.out
coverage.*
*.log

# Editor swap files.
*.swp
*.swo

# TypeScript build cache.
*.tsbuildinfo

# E2E run artefacts.
e2e/test-results
e2e/playwright-report
